The following is a '''list of glam metal bands and artists''' with articles on Wikipedia. The list includes bands and artists that have been described as [[glam metal]] or its interchangeable terms, hair metal<ref name="Noisecreep1">{{cite web|url=http://www.noisecreep.com/2010/01/01/top-10-musicians-with-hair-metal-pasts/|title=Top 10 Musicians with Hair Metal Pasts - Noisecreep|last=Ramirez|first=Carlos|publisher=[[Noisecreep]]|accessdate=18 April 2010}}</ref> & hair bands,<ref>{{cite book | url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PpX6xBSj-MQC&pg=PT7&dq=glam+metal+hair+band&cd=2#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=History of Rock Bands | author=Witmer, Scott | page=22 |year=2010 | isbn=978-1-60453-692-8}}</ref> as well as being used synonymously with pop metal<ref name=AllmusicPop-Metal>[{{Allmusic|class=explore|id=style/d7728|pure_url=yes}} "Pop-metal"], ''Allmusic''. Retrieved 9 November 2011.</ref> by professional journalists at some stage in their career. Glam metal is a [[subgenre]] of [[heavy metal music|heavy metal]].<ref name="Headbanger's journey">{{cite web|url=http://jam.canoe.ca/Movies/2006/02/24/1460062.html|title=CANOE -- JAM! Movies: 'Headbanger' is Heavy Metal: 101|last=Stevenson|first=Jane|publisher=[[JAM!]]|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> Heavily influenced by 1970s [[glam rock]],<ref name="Hair metal">{{cite web|url=http://heavymetal.about.com/od/heavymetal101/p/hairmetal.htm|title=What Is Hair Metal? - History of Hair Metal - Hair Metal 101 - About.com|last=Bowar|first=Chad|publisher=[[About.com]]|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> the music of glam metal typically mixed heavy metal, [[pop music]], and [[hard rock]].<ref name="Hair metal Allmusic">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=explore|id=style/d2693|pure_url=yes}}|title=allmusic|publisher=[[Allmusic]]|accessdate=25 May 2010}}</ref> Glam metal groups were also known for their visual attire which typically included teased hair, makeup, and showy clothing.<ref name="Hair metal Allmusic" /> Glam metal was predominately successful in the 1980s, though the rise of [[grunge]] during the 1990s caused its popularity to decline. However in the 2000s, several glam metal groups began to regain interest.<ref name="Hair metal" />
